# Real Browser MCP

MCP server: `user-real-browser-mcp`. Controls the user's REAL Chrome browser - not headless. All sessions, logins, cookies are already active.

## Rules

- NEVER close tabs you didn't create
- NEVER navigate away from pages the user is working on without asking
- Prefer `browser_snapshot` over `browser_screenshot` (cheaper, faster, parseable)
- Snapshots return refs that break after navigation/scroll/DOM changes - always re-snapshot before using stale refs
- DO NOT default to `browser_evaluate` for UI interactions â€” it fails on strict-CSP sites (GitHub, Google, etc.)

## Tools

### Navigation & Tabs
- `browser_navigate` - Go to URL. Params: `url`, `waitUntil`
- `browser_tabs` - List/create/close/focus tabs. Params: `action` (list|create|close|focus), `tabId`, `url`

### Interaction
- `browser_click` - Click element by ref OR CSS selector. Params: `ref`, `selector`, `button` (left|right|middle), `doubleClick`
- `browser_click_text` - Click element by visible text. CSP-safe. Best for dropdowns/menus. Params: `text`, `index` (0-based), `exact` (boolean)
- `browser_type` - Type text. Params: `ref` OR `selector`, `text`, `clear`
- `browser_press_key` - Keyboard. Params: `key`, `modifiers` (ctrl|alt|shift|meta), `ref`, `selector`
- `browser_scroll` - Scroll. Params: `direction`, `amount`, `selector`, `toElement`, `position` (top|bottom)
- `browser_hover` - Hover element. Params: `ref` OR `selector`
- `browser_select` - Select from native `<select>`. Params: `ref` OR `selector`, `value` OR `label` OR `index`

### Reading
- `browser_snapshot` - Accessibility tree with refs. Params: `selector`
- `browser_screenshot` - Capture visible tab as image. Params: `format` (png|jpeg), `quality`
- `browser_text` - Get text content. Params: `selector`, `maxLength`
- `browser_find` - Find elements by natural language. Params: `query`, `limit`

### JavaScript & Dialogs
- `browser_evaluate` - Execute JS via chrome.debugger CDP. Bypasses CSP but shows debugger banner and may close popups. Use as LAST RESORT only.
- `browser_handle_dialog` - Handle alert/confirm/prompt. Call BEFORE triggering actions that cause dialogs. Params: `action` (accept|dismiss), `promptText`

### Waiting
- `browser_wait` - Wait for element or delay. Params: `selector`, `state` (visible|hidden|attached), `timeout`, `delay`

### Debug
- `browser_console` - Read console messages (read-only). Params: `clear`
- `browser_network` - Read network requests. Params: `filter` (regex), `clear`

## React Dropdowns / Portals / Overlays (IMPORTANT)

Snapshot refs DO NOT capture React portal overlays (rendered outside main DOM tree). DO NOT use `browser_evaluate` â€” it uses chrome.debugger which steals focus and closes the dropdown.

Proven pattern that works on all sites including strict-CSP (GitHub, Google):

1. `browser_click` on the trigger button (use ref from snapshot)
2. `browser_wait` with `delay: 400` for the overlay to render
3. `browser_text` with broad CSS selectors to confirm dropdown is open and read options:
   `"selector": "[role=menu],[role=listbox],.ActionList,.SelectMenu-list,.Overlay,details-menu"`
4. `browser_click` with a CSS selector targeting the desired child:
   `"selector": ".ActionList li:first-child"` or use `browser_click_text` with the option text

If `browser_click_text` is available, prefer it â€” it finds elements by visible text, picks the deepest DOM match, and is CSP-safe.

## Social Media Sites (X/Twitter, LinkedIn, Reddit)

These sites use virtual scroll, React-controlled inputs, and heavy CSP. Patterns learned from real usage:

### Scrolling

`browser_scroll` `amount` is **pixels**, not pages. Default 500px barely moves a feed. Use 2000-3000 to load new content. Always `browser_wait` with `delay: 2000` after scrolling for content to render, then re-read with `browser_text`.

### Reading feeds and search results

- `browser_text` with `selector: "section[role='region']"` and `maxLength: 15000` is the fastest way to read a Twitter/X timeline or search results. Returns all tweet text, usernames, dates, and engagement counts as plain text.
- `browser_snapshot` on the same selector gives you refs + status URLs (look for `href` containing `/status/`).
- Combine both: text to read content, snapshot to get clickable refs and URLs.

### Twitter/X search

Build search URLs directly. Key operators:
- `from:username` - tweets by a specific user
- `"exact phrase"` - exact match
- `(word1 OR word2)` - alternatives
- `-filter:replies` - exclude replies
- `min_faves:N` - minimum likes
- `&f=live` at the end for latest results, omit for top/relevance

Example: `https://x.com/search?q=from%3Ausername%20%22keyword%22&src=typed_query`

### Replying on Twitter/X

1. Navigate to the tweet URL (`/username/status/ID`)
2. `browser_wait` with `delay: 3000` for full load
3. `browser_snapshot` with `selector: "[data-testid='tweetTextarea_0']"` to find reply box
4. `browser_click` the ref to focus
5. `browser_type` the reply text (Twitter limit: 280 chars - count BEFORE typing, you cannot easily clear and retype)
6. `browser_wait` with `delay: 1500` for link card preview to load
7. `browser_click` with `selector: "[data-testid='tweetButtonInline']"` to submit

### contentEditable gotchas (applies to all social sites)

- `browser_type` with `clear: true` does NOT work on contentEditable divs (Twitter, LinkedIn composers). React's state doesn't update from `textContent = ''`.
- `browser_press_key` for Cmd+A / Backspace dispatches events but doesn't trigger native text selection in contentEditable.
- If you type the wrong thing, **reload the page** and start over. Faster than fighting the editor.
- Always pre-calculate character limits before typing. You get one shot.

### LinkedIn posting

Reply box selector: `[data-testid='editor']` or `.ql-editor`. Same contentEditable rules apply. Character limit: 3000 for posts, 1250 for comments.

### Reddit

Old reddit is easier to automate (plain HTML forms). New reddit uses React with similar contentEditable issues as Twitter.

## Workflow

1. `browser_snapshot` to see page structure and get element refs
2. Use refs with `browser_click`, `browser_type`, etc.
3. For dropdowns/menus: follow the pattern above (click trigger -> wait -> text -> click child)
4. After actions, re-snapshot or `browser_find` to verify result
5. `browser_wait` before interacting with dynamically loaded content
6. `browser_press_key` for keyboard shortcuts (Enter to submit, Escape to close modals)
